Jun 18 2008 	A nice little pad up in town.	This review deliberatley concentrates on the bad bits - Overall the experience was excellent.It was a late booking so we did not get the chance to check out the hotel on Trip Advisor first - Luckily, as if we had we may have been put off by the reports about the noise. We were there for one night only and as it was mid week we probably avoided the possible problems associated with parties. We did get some noise during the day coming from the building works below (They are still fitting out the shops under the apartments and I feel we should have been warned of this when we booked) but this was not a problem after about 18:00. The only other negative aspect of our stay was caused by the fact that this is Marlin Apartments not a Hotel. You have to pick up your keys from the Concierge. The entrance is not well signposted and was locked when we arrived. We had to ring the bell for the Concierge and than stood around waiting for quite some time before being let in. We given the keys to an apartment on the first floor. When we booked, we had requested a balcony but the conciege could not confirm that we had one, and in any case stated that they could not change the allocated apartment themselves as they only handed out keys - if we had a problem then we would have to go through the central booking system to get anything changed. Luckily, this proved not to be necessary.Our apartment was very clean and tidy, modern and well equipped (as per other reviews). It had a small balcony, although being on the first floor and facing in to the central courtyard this proved not to be that useful (Ask for an apartment higher up and on the outside if the city view is important to you). The bed was large and comfy. The curtains blocked out the light quite well (although the apartment would benefit from net curtains as the floor to ceiling windows do leave you feeling a bit &quot;on show&quot; ). There was no appreciable street noise. We had an excellent nights sleep.Location was excellent, Tesco Express (Supermarket) is practically on site and open 7:00 till 23:00. There are plenty of bars and restaurants within easy reach with the City centre only 10 minutes walk away.Overall this is an excellent place to stay if you need to be in London for a few days. The price is cheaper than any of the nearby hotels (booked direct with marlin website) and you get more space and better facilities thrown in unless you particulaly like using hotel room service or need an onsite restaurant. The next time we need a place to stay in this area we will definitely have this at the top of our value for money list.	
Jun 12 2008 	Fab apartment - shame about the noise...	I was encouraged by all of the positive reviews on this site and elsewhere, and of the possibility of having some space, and a kitchen, in London, so booked a 1 bedroom flat for the weekend.The apartment itself was fantastic: as everyone has noted, immaculately clean, spacious, well decorated, really everything one could hope for.The major downside for me was the noise. The building itself is extremely badly soundproofed, with very heavy fire doors, both going into the apartment, and within the apartment itself, which meant we could hear everyone coming back, etc. Some of the apartments also look out onto a courtyard, and even on the fifth floor, it's possible to hear people speaking in normal voices down below.Secondly, possibly because of the size of the apartments, there seemed to be a lot of people who had come for the weekend to party, and spend a lot of time going back and forth between each other's apartments until well past 2. I read on another site that these apartments are popular with hen and stag nights...Finally, on the other side of the courtyard are apartments that are rented out long term. There was a very loud party in one apartment that went on throughout the night and into the next morning. When I went down, at 4:30 to complain about the noise, I was told that the management could do nothing about it, but I could call an environmental health number myself so that they could measure the decibels over the phone from the apartment, which seemed like a bit of a faff. I asked to be moved to another apartment, and was told that the people at the front desk could only hand out keys, and I'd need to contact Marlin Apartments during office hours the next day.So I felt it was a real shame, as the apartment was ideal, but after two sleepless nights, I'd think again next time. I'd be curious to know if the other Marlin apartments in London suffer from the same problems or not.	
